mportant to him, his father shut him down. A key turning point involving his artistic aspirations came in 1979, when he participated in the National Bible Competition and won his first sculpture competition. His father\'s reaction, predictably, was rejection; he broke all of his son\'s artwork by hurling it against a wall. By his father\'s intentional discouragement of Anton\'s artistic talent, he created an even more determined son who would try to prove his father wrong for the rest of his life. He wanted his father to believe in him to make a success and a living from being an artist. His father was promoted to the position of the first official Liaison Officer of the Police, ironically drawing on his vast experience in Communication. Anton describes him [/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column width=\"1/3\"]<!--nextpage-->[vc_column_text] as \"a vivacious personality with a strong sense of justice\" who performed Shakespeare and sang opera. He was stationed at the Pretoria headquarters and set up the Public Liaison Department, thereafter being promoted to divisional Commissioner West Rand with its headquarters in Krugersdorp. After matriculating, Anton did not have enough funds to go to university. His parents could only afford to support one child\'s further studies, which was his youngest brother, (now an expert in quantum physics). As a budding artist, Anton had no assistance, he was on his own. He spent the next few years, from 1971 to 1973, in the Police Academy under his father\'s command. Here his problem with the system resurfaced as he refused to cut his hair and to use a firearm. In doing so he was treated as a very difficult, unruly individual who had to be tamed or \"broke-in\"; labelled a \"hippie\" and treated with disdain. At the Police Academy, Anton revelled in all law-related subjects and excelled with a 93% average. \"Later in my police career and life I tried to apply what I was taught at Law school, but this didn\'t work out so well for me…\" While in the police, Anton became aware of the unjustness of the apartheid regime and the cruel and unjustifiable application of racial discrimination. He became a passive activist, putting greater strain on the already precarious relationship with his father, who had been promoted to Major General in charge of personnel. Being fundamentally unfit to serve or fit into the system, in 1976 his father removed him from active police duty, instead sending him to work in the Police Museum (SAP Photography). \"I was a problem and a disgrace to my father\'s career, and he ‘organised\' me a job at the Police Museum, where I learnt how to take crime pictures. It was fascinating to go into the darkroom to develop pictures. Ironically, through this system I so despised I found myself learning lots of interesting things like how to read fingerprinting.\" He discovered the dark side of police photography, documenting serious crime scenes and murders, developing the crime photos trying to discover the truth. He found it intriguing to be part of the investigating team. \"I started having more and more haunting nightmares and realised I had to go. I did not complete my tour of duty at the police and was therefore commanded to do duty at the local police station for the period of one month every year for five years, which I duly did.\" During this time Anton joined Kraft Pottery down in the basement of the SALU building in Andries Street, Pretoria. \"This was my escape from the real world, where I started making ceramic sculptures. Often I was not able to drive back home on my 150cc motorbike and found myself sleeping in the pottery studio under a table.\" He took various jobs from 1975 to 1977 to make ends meet, working as a window designer at Greatermans and Garlicks, taking care of his first wife Erica and his son Sydney. [/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width=\"2/3\"][vc_row_inner][vc_column_inner width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text] Anton was employed as a security guard at Datsun Nissan (1977 to 1980) and as a security officer at SA Breweries (1980 to 1982) until he found a much better paid job at Steel Mobile in Rosslyn. He used his scooter for transportation and was soon doing night duty: \"This I\'ve organised in order to sustain my artistic hobby going to Kraft pottery during the day, starting night duty from 10pm till 6am. We were desperately poor. I came home, napped for an hour or two after night shift and then went to Kraft Pottery where I worked all day. I knew I had to force myself in order to get out of the poverty trap. \"This was also a form of escapism from my dire home circumstances. I had to make it on my own in order to prove my father wrong. He never gave me any form of financial support.\"</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>\"Experience is a tough taskmaster. First you have to write the test, before you get the lesson.\" - Sol Kerzner - At this time he achieved his first artistic breakthroughs and in 1977 he received special mention in the South African Art Association\'s New Signatures competition. Two years later he had a great boost when he won first prize in the New Signatures competition in Pretoria. \"Miraculously the works [/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text] I made at the pottery were getting a lot of attention and it started to sell,\" he recalls. He was the \"Artist of the month\" in 1982 at the Pretoria Art Museum and that year he quit his job at SA Breweries security. This was followed in 1987 with his first one man exhibition in the Beuster-Skolimowski Gallery in Pretoria and in 1989 another one man exhibition at the SAAA. After a few years of doing something which he felt passionate about, he could afford to build a studio in the backyard of a rented house in Vallieria. \"At this stage my older brother resigned his work and desperately wanted to work with me. Together we started making pots and garden products, some of which became household goods.\" The ne