 cruel and unjustifiable application of racial discrimination. He became a passive activist, putting greater strain on the already precarious relationship with his father, who had been promoted to Major General in charge of personnel. Being fundamentally unfit to serve or fit into the system, in 1976 his father removed him from active police duty, instead sending him to work in the Police Museum (SAP Photography). \"I was a problem and a disgrace to my father\'s career, and he ‘organised\' me a job at the Police Museum, where I learnt how to take crime pictures. It was fascinating to go into the darkroom to develop pictures. Ironically, through this system I so despised I found myself learning lots of interesting things like how to read fingerprinting.\" He discovered the dark side of police photography, documenting serious crime scenes and murders, developing the crime photos trying to discover the truth. He found it intriguing to be part of the investigating team. \"I started having more and more haunting nightmares and realised I had to go. I did not complete my tour of duty at the police and was therefore commanded to do duty at the local police station for the period of one month every year for five years, which I duly did.\" During this time Anton joined Kraft Pottery down in the basement of the SALU building in Andries Street, Pretoria. \"This was my escape from the real world, where I started making ceramic sculptures. Often I was not able to drive back home on my 150cc motorbike and found myself sleeping in the pottery studio under a table.\" He took various jobs from 1975 to 1977 to make ends meet, working as a window designer at Greatermans and Garlicks, taking care of his first wife Erica and his son Sydney. [/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width=\"2/3\"][vc_row_inner][vc_column_inner width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text] Anton was employed as a security guard at Datsun Nissan (1977 to 1980) and as a security officer at SA Breweries (1980 to 1982) until 