ctures. Ironically, through this system I so despised I found myself learning lots of interesting things like how to read fingerprinting.\" He discovered the dark side of police photography, documenting serious crime scenes and murders, developing the crime photos trying to discover the truth. He found it intriguing to be part of the investigating team.</p>\r\n<p>\"I started having more and more haunting nightmares and realised I had to go. I did not complete my tour of duty at the police and was therefore commanded to do duty at the local police station for the period of one month every year for five years, which I duly did.\"</p>\r\n<p>During this time Anton joined Kraft Pottery down in the basement of the SALU building in Andries Street, Pretoria. \"This was my escape from the real world, where I started making ceramic sculptures. Often I was not able to drive back home on my 150cc motorbike and found myself sleeping in the pottery studio under a table.\"</p>\r\n<p>He took various jobs from 1975 to 1977 to make ends meet, working as a window designer at Greatermans and Garlicks, taking care of his first wife Erica and his son Sydney.</p>\r\n<p>[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width=\"2/3\"][vc_row_inner][vc_column_inner width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text]</p>\r\n<p>Anton was employed as a security guard at Datsun Nissan (1977 to 1980) and as a security officer at SA Breweries (1980 to 1982) until he found a much better paid job at Steel Mobile in Rosslyn. He used his scooter for transportation and was soon doing night duty: \"This I\'ve organised in order to sustain my artistic hobby going to Kraft pottery during the day, starting night duty from 10pm till 6am. We were desperately poor. I came home, napped for an hour or two after night shift and then went to Kraft Pottery where I worked all day. I knew I had to force myself in order to get out of the poverty trap. \"This was also a form of escapism from my dire home circumstances. I had to make it on my own in order to prove my father wrong. He never gave me any form of financial support.\"</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><em>\"Experience is a tough taskmaster. First you have to write the test, before you get the lesson.\"</em><br /> - Sol Kerzner -</p>\r\n<p>At this time he achieved his first artistic breakthroughs and in 1977 he received special mention in the South African Art Association\'s New Signatures competition. Two years later he had a great boost when he won first prize in the New Signatures competition in Pretoria. \"Miraculously the works</p>\r\n<p>[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text]</p>\r\n<p>I made at the pottery were getting a lot of attention and it started to sell,\" he recalls.</p>\r\n<p>He was the \"Artist of the month\" in 1982 at the Pretoria Art Museum and that year he quit his job at SA Breweries security. This was followed in 1987 with his first one man exhibition in the Beuster-Skolimowski Gallery in Pretoria and in 1989 another one man exhibition at the SAAA.</p>\r\n<p>After a few years of doing something which he felt passionate about, he could afford to build a studio in the backyard of a rented house in Vallieria. \"At this stage my older brother resigned his work and desperately wanted to work with me. Together we started making pots and garden products, some of which became household goods.\" The new venture was called Anorica, a trademark that became well known at garden shops and nationwide nurseries like Plant Topia and Plant Park, where these items were stocked. Anton designed most of the items while Ethan handled the casting. \"This put food on the table for several years,\" Anton recounts. \"Later I became less and less involved, trying to pursue my own career as a sculptor.\"</p>\r\n<p>Anton handed his share over to his brother in 1990, at the same time he was also in partnership with Style Décor, making all kinds of stylish products, and later selling the business.</p>\r\n<p>[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][/vc_row_inner][vc_single_image image=\"502\" border_color=\"grey\" img_link_target=\"_self\" img_size=\"large\"][/vc_column][/vc_row]<!--nextpage-->[vc_row][vc_column width=\"1/3\"][vc_column_text]</p>\r\n<p><em>“Go big or go home!”</em><br /> - Sol Kerzner -</p>\r\n<p>“Gradually my artwork became more popular and by 1990 I was at last selling enough to make a living and could commit myself full time to art. I could then afford to buy my first house in Vallieria, Pretoria.”</p>\r\n<p>Anton launched a lighting business, Let There Be Light, designing and manufacturing artistic light designs and selling these to décor shops like Future Classics. His first studio was in Vallieria, where he held many exhibitions. Since then he has held numerous exhibitions of his sculptures throughout South Africa, in the Pretoria Art Museum, in Witrivier, Nelspruit, Pietersburg, Johannesburg, Potchefstroom, Durban, Cape Town, in leading galleries such as the Crake, Kraft, Olivetti, Michaelatos, Beuster-Skolimowski, Everard Read and many others. His work has been exhibited in Rome and Milan, Italy. The M-Net Head Office bought large sculptures, and he completed commissioned works for BMW’s head office in Johannesburg.</p>\r\n<p>In 1994, he put 35 sculptures on exhibition in New York at the Jacob Jawitz Exhibition Centre and Grand Central Station as part of the “Strengthening the Link” initiative to boost the trade between South Africa and The United States, organised by SATOUR in conjunction with the Department of Trade and Industry, represented by Nelson Mandela. He considers one of the highlights of his career The Age of Grace, an eight foot high bronze sculpture at Grand Central Station which celebrated South African Heritage, and was displayed on the front cover of The New York Times.</p>\r\n<p>Anton Rupert bought one of Smit’s works for the Rembrandt Foundation. A collection of his work was exhibited during the inauguration of the late President Nelson Mandela at the Union Buildings in Pretoria in 1994. Nobel Laureate Desmond Tutu and ex-minister Pik Botha bought some of his sculptures. He created a striking series of sculptures for the Boardwalk Meander in Pretoria.</p>\r\n<p>His work has been lauded internationally in places as diverse as Rome and Milan, Italy (1991), the Sweeguan Art Gallery in Singapore (1993), Bonn and Wolfsburg in Germany (1994), the SA Embassy in Bonn (1998), Amsterdam (2004) and Cologne (2014).</p>\r\n<p>In 2003, Smit opened his own sculpture garden, the spectacular Anton Smit Sculpture Park in Aqua Vista, with a breathtaking view of Bronkhorstspruit Dam. In the same year he created the enormous Sandstone Head (2 x 3 metres) for a European art collector.</p>\r\n<p>The Anton Smit Sculpture Park, a unique outdoor exhibition which is a mere 40 minutes’ drive from Pretoria and 60 minutes from Johannesburg, is a destination of creativity attracting tourists and art buyers locally and internationally. The Sculpture Park’s three-hectare grounds</p>\r\n<p>[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width=\"1/3\"][vc_column_text]</p>\r\n<p>Prolific</p>\r\n<p>Other landmark exhibitions and art commissions he completed include the Public Commission National library of Tshwane in Pretoria (2007); No Second Death Exhibition in Franchhoek at the Grande Provence Wine Estate and Gallery (2009); a large sandstone head and other art commissioned by Graff Delaire Wine Estate (2009); Facets exhibition and Angels exhibition at the Anton Smit Gallery (2010); Transitions at Anton Smit Gallery and Faith exhibition at the Grande Hyatt Regency Hotel and Golf Estate Oubaai (2011); Transcendental Head/Kungwini public sculpture on the R25, a symbol of the new SA (2012); Metal work exhibition in Stellenbosch and The Continuous Redemption of Man at the Gallery on Liviseur, Bloemfontein, Innibos festival in Nelspruit (2013); Art Affair at the Saxon Hotel in Johannesburg (2014), Transections in the Youngblood Gallery in Cape Town and a monumental commission for Menlyn Maine (2014). He is also a participant in the Cool Capital initiative of Tshwane.</p>\r\n<p>Anton Smit’s much-anticipated solo sculpture exhibition Reverberating Time was shown at the Youngblood Gallery in Cape Town in March 2014. Half of the pieces in this solo exhibition were displayed there for three days, then sent to Germany, where Youngblood Europe presented them as part of the world-renowned contemporary art fair, Art Cologne.</p>\r\n<p>--- in a block?</p>\r\n<p>are situated on the northern side of the Bronkhorstspruit Dam, on a plateau overlooking the water. Among the backdrop of natural limestone formations, manicured lawns and succulent gardens, it makes for a lovely environment to view the expansive collection of monumental sculptures and exhibitions, including the Imagine Café, a full service coffee shop. The Park expands the traditional concept of an art venue, ensuring a truly unique and inspiring experience.</p>\r\n<p>Here he created a monumental sculpture wall on the theme of Revelations (2008), the last book of the New Testament. “It doesn’t represent the narrative or try to tell the interwoven stories of Revelations or pretend to issue any prophetic warning. I didn’t want to knock together generic or kitsch images like news pictures in Time Magazine. Rather, it deals thematically with the emotional impact of Revelations on the human race, all the spiritual drama wrought by so much upheaval. I certainly did not want to be predictable…”</p>\r\n<p>The epic art wall is populated with entwined figures who struggle in the grip of powerful emotions. There are 50 or more human figures in the wall, but no animals. But there is a central fish.” The figures, varying from hand-sized to one and a half times lifesized, seem to twist and turn</p>\r\n<p>[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width=\"1/3\"][vc_column_text]</p>\r\n<p>and writhe in constant motion. “In the perfect logic of our dreams, Jonah’s whale is the Leviathan seeking to swallow our future by hiding purpose and direction.”</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><em>“An artist is a paradox. By being selfish he becomes unselfish.”</em><br /> - Anton Smit -</p>\r\n<p>As his work was becoming more visible to the public and open to criticism, Anton took part in exhibitions which placed strain on his first marriage. He was divorced in 1999, after his second son Lionel matriculated. A new era dawned in 1999 when he bought a farm in Derdepoort, Pretoria, where he had his studio at – on the Kameeldrift road. In 2000, work was commissioned by The University of Pretoria. In 2001, his works were purchased by the Rembrandt Foundation in Stellenbosch and a large work was commissioned by MNT Developers for the Boardwalk Meander.</p>\r\n<p>[/vc_column_text][vc_single_image image=\"509\" border_color=\"grey\" img_link_target=\"_self\" img_size=\"large\"][/vc_column][/vc_row]</p>','Biography','','inherit','open','open','','482-revision-v1','','','2014-10-21 10:32:26','2014-10-21 08:32:26','',482,'http://192.168.1.11/ANTONSMIT/website/htdocs/482-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(512,1,'2014-10-21 10:35:22','2014-10-21 08:35:22','<p>[vc_row][vc_column width=\"1/3\"][vc_column_text] <em>\"What distinguishes the creative person is his persistence and determination to excel.\"</em> - Rhoma Ochse - Anton Smit collects sayings and quotations about the relationship between art and the individual artist\'s experience of reality. \"Art is not to render the visible but to render visible,\" he asserts, and his art achieves this in many ways. An inspiring raconteur, Anton loves to relate tales about his struggle as a young artist. The secret to his success could be attributed to his courage and determination to forge ahead in the face of great difficulty. \"Take big risks. Don\'t fret about what others think. Do the most difficult thing on earth for you – do it for yourself.\" This approach paid off in spades. Widely revered for his overwhelming heads and monumental sculptures, evoking themes of suffering, reconciliation, glory and sublimation, his works grace public and private collections countrywide and internationally.</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><em>\"A human being consists of the choices he makes.\"</em> - Anton Smit - Anton Smit was born on 2 August 1954 in Boksburg, South Africa, on the back seat of a car on the way to the hospital outside the Colgate factory. His father was a police officer, his beloved mother a teacher, of whom he paints a vivid picture: \"My mother was a beauty from Moorreesburg with long wavy hair down to her hips. There was a posed studiophotograph done in the forties post-war sepia-toned style with her looking up, her face awash in a mystical heavenly light. I doted over this photo as a child; it filled me with warmth and confidence that I could achieve anything I wanted. Alas, she passed away in 1981 spending her dying moments – so the sisters told me – in the same hospital bed in Port Shepstone as Walter Battis did a few months earlier. She was cremated in Durban and her ashes somehow got lost. I was overwhelmed with a sense of unbearable loss and vented my grief on creating a sculpture in a trance-like state, until my brother walked into the studio and exclaimed: ‘Oh, I see you\'ve made a sculpture of mom\'s photo, what a remarkable resemblance!\' Ever since then I have always kept that sculpture outside my studio as a memorial to my mother, so instead of occasionally visiting her grave, she is with me every day.\" With his father posted to different stations, the family moved several times over the years. He was raised in Boksburg till the age of three, in Grahamstown till four, and in Port Shepstone from the ages of four to eight. Most of his formative years were spent in Kwa-Zulu Natal. His father was stationed in Port Shepstone as Captain Regional Commander. [/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width=\"1/3\"][vc_single_image image=\"487\" border_color=\"grey\" img_link_target=\"_self\" img_size=\"large\"][vc_column_text] Anton has fond memories of this period and recalls himself as a carefree child, playing outside with bare feet, a fearless young Tarzan disappearing into the tropical forest for hours, with a wooden stick as a knife and a kettie defending himself against an imaginary enemy. He stole and ate mangoes from the neighbours and sold them, his first encounter with the learning of business skills. He went to school from a very young age. His mother was a teacher who could not let him stay at home alone, and from the age of four she took him along to school where he attended grade 1 over two years ahead of his peer group and doing extremely well. Attending the only school in Port Shepstone, he learnt English second language at a very young age. He recalls raucous rivalries between the two language groups, calling each other names like \"Afrikaner vrot Benaner!\" and \"Rooinek, parrabek, trap jou vrek!\" As a most inquisitive child Anton discovered art at a very young age paging through glossy publications such as Life Magazine and Reader\'s Digest, and in one such magazine he first saw the sculpture Pieta by Michelangelo. Not being able to read properly he thought it was made by the angel Micheal. \"I thought no human being could be capable of making such a beautiful thing…\" Once he discovered it was made by a human being called Michelangelo (with the surname Bionarotti), he said to himself that if that could be possible, he might also be able to make something as beautiful as the Pieta one day. \"To this day this is to me the most significant artwork of all times – it brings tears to my eyes every time I look at it…\" In 1967 he was in standard 7 in Voortrekker High, Bloemfontein, where he found himself bored with school, scoring high marks in maths and science but not stimulated enough: \"I knew the equations off by heart already, and I became a burdened child questioning the answers to school questions. [/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width=\"1/3\"][vc_column_text] I was always fascinated by things outside the system…\" In an attempt to stimulate and subdue his prickly personality, Anton was moved to the well known Grey College in standard 8, where he didn\'t fit in at all. He discovered a joy in swimming and joined the school swimming team, becoming a part-time lifesaver at the public swimming pool. This was partly a way to escape difficult circumstances at home. \"Things were starting to pick up for me,\" he remembers. \"I had excellent marks at school, and I was offered an opportunity to swim provincially representing my school, but my father refused. Then we had to move again because Father was promoted to general.\" Moving from a platteland community to a school in Oos Moot in the big city Pretoria had a profoundly negative impact on the young Anton. It was becoming evident that the relationship between his parents was very strained. Anton begged his father to leave him in Bloemfontein to attend boarding school, while the family moved to Pretoria. His father refused, asking him: \"Who will be looking after your mother then?\" Anton was the one who had to deal with his mother\'s delicate state of mind, while his father was mostly absent due to official duties. When not busy with police work, his father was attending \"Boys Nights\", social events, playing golf or performing in plays; he was never available for the family, occupied with \"more important matters\", while Anton interpreted this absence as his father neglecting and dropping his family entirely. By this time Anton\'s older brother Ethan had already left school to join the armed forces on the border. In standard 9 and 10 (1970 to 1971) in Oos Moot he was becoming a rebel, questioning the system and the rule of authoritarian figures like his father and the headmaster. He resisted the unnecessarily strict rules and military way the headmaster presided over the school, severe punishment by rottang. He chafed from a severe lack of communication with his father. Whenever he wanted to discuss matters important to him, his father shut him down. A key turning point involving his artistic aspirations came in 1979, when he participated in the National Bible Competition and won his first sculpture competition. His father\'s reaction, predictably, was rejection; he broke all of his son\'s artwork by hurling it against a wall. By his father\'s intentional discouragement of Anton\'s artistic talent, he created an even more determined son who would try to prove his father wrong for the rest of his life. He wanted his father to believe in him to make a success and a living from being an artist. His father was promoted to the position of the first official Liaison Officer of the Police, ironically drawing on his vast experience in Communication. Anton describes him [/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column][vc_column_text]<!--nextpage-->[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column width=\"1/3\"][vc_column_text] as \"a vivacious personality with a strong sense of justice\" who performed Shakespeare and sang opera. He was stationed at the Pretoria headquarters and set up the Public Liaison Department, thereafter being promoted to divisional Commissioner West Rand with its headquarters in Krugersdorp. After matriculating, Anton did not have enough funds to go to university. His parents could only afford to support one child\'s further studies, which was his youngest brother, (now an expert in quantum physics). As a budding artist, Anton had no assistance, he was on his own. He spent the next few years, from 1971 to 1973, in the Police Academy under his father\'s command. Here his problem with the system resurfaced as he refused to cut his hair and to use a firearm. In doing so he was treated as a very difficult, unruly individual who had to be tamed or \"broke-in\"; labelled a \"hippie\" and treated with disdain. At the Police Academy, Anton revelled in all law-related subjects and excelled with